1
00:00:09,209 --> 00:00:14,097
"we have shared the incommunicable
experience of war.

2
00:00:14,097 --> 00:00:17,350
"we have felt, we still feel,

3
00:00:17,350 --> 00:00:20,603
the passion of life to its top."

4
00:00:21,688 --> 00:00:26,026
our hearts were touched with fire."

5
00:00:26,026 --> 00:00:28,194
oliver wendell holmes.

6
00:00:33,066 --> 00:00:35,785
[explosions]

7
00:00:35,785 --> 00:00:37,404
By the summer of 1861,

8
00:00:37,404 --> 00:00:39,572
wilmer mclean had had enough.

9
00:00:40,123 --> 00:00:41,207
[explosion]

10
00:00:41,207 --> 00:00:44,411
two great armies were
converging on his farm,

11
00:00:44,411 --> 00:00:45,495
and what would be

12
00:00:45,495 --> 00:00:47,130
the first major battle
of the civil war--

13
00:00:47,130 --> 00:00:49,299
bull run, or manassas,

14
00:00:49,299 --> 00:00:50,917
as the confederates
called it--

15
00:00:51,468 --> 00:00:54,721
would soon rage across
the aging virginian's farm,

16
00:00:54,721 --> 00:00:56,339
a union shell going so far

17
00:00:56,339 --> 00:00:59,059
as to explode
in the summer kitchen.

18
00:01:01,227 --> 00:01:04,481
now mclean moved his family
away from manassas,

19
00:01:04,481 --> 00:01:06,649
far south and west
of richmond,

20
00:01:06,649 --> 00:01:08,268
out of harm's way,
he prayed,

21
00:01:08,268 --> 00:01:10,437
to a dusty
little crossroads

22
00:01:10,437 --> 00:01:13,156
called appomattox courthouse.

23
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:15,859
and it was there
in his living room,

24
00:01:15,859 --> 00:01:17,494
3 1/2 years later,

25
00:01:17,494 --> 00:01:20,196
that lee
surrendered to grant.

26
00:01:21,281 --> 00:01:24,000
and wilmer mclean
could rightfully say,

27
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:26,169
"the war began
in my front yard

28
00:01:26,169 --> 00:01:28,872
and ended
in my front parlor."

29
00:03:10,139 --> 00:03:12,859
the civil war was fought
in 10,000 places

30
00:03:12,859 --> 00:03:14,477
from valverde,
new mexico,

31
00:03:15,028 --> 00:03:16,646
and tullahoma, tennessee,

32
00:03:17,197 --> 00:03:18,281
to st. albans, vermont,

33
00:03:18,815 --> 00:03:21,534
and fernandina on
the florida coast.

34
00:03:24,153 --> 00:03:26,873
more than 3 million
americans fought in it,

35
00:03:26,873 --> 00:03:30,660
and over 600,000 men,
2% of the population,

36
00:03:31,211 --> 00:03:32,829
died in it.

37
00:03:35,548 --> 00:03:38,251
american homes
became headquarters.

38
00:03:38,251 --> 00:03:40,420
american churches
and schoolhouses

39
00:03:40,420 --> 00:03:43,673
sheltered the dying...

40
00:03:43,673 --> 00:03:48,011
and huge foraging armies
swept across american farms

41
00:03:48,011 --> 00:03:51,264
and burned
american towns.

42
00:03:53,433 --> 00:03:56,653
americans slaughtered
one another wholesale here,

43
00:03:56,653 --> 00:03:59,355
in america,
in their own corn fields

44
00:03:59,355 --> 00:04:00,990
and peach orchards,

45
00:04:00,990 --> 00:04:01,941
along familiar roads,

46
00:04:01,941 --> 00:04:06,279
and by waters with
old american names.

47
00:04:07,814 --> 00:04:09,282
in two days at shiloh,

48
00:04:09,282 --> 00:04:11,451
on the banks
of the tennessee,

49
00:04:11,451 --> 00:04:13,620
more american men fell

50
00:04:13,620 --> 00:04:16,873
than in all previous
american wars combined.

51
00:04:19,459 --> 00:04:20,543
at cold harbor,

52
00:04:20,543 --> 00:04:25,431
7,000 americans fell
in 20 minutes.

53
00:04:33,022 --> 00:04:34,641
men who had
never strayed 20 miles

54
00:04:34,641 --> 00:04:36,276
from their
own front doors

55
00:04:36,276 --> 00:04:39,529
now found themselves
soldiers in great armies,

56
00:04:39,529 --> 00:04:43,316
fighting epic battles
hundreds of miles from home.

57
00:04:46,035 --> 00:04:48,204
they knew
they were making history,

58
00:04:48,204 --> 00:04:51,457
and it was the greatest
adventure of their lives.

59
00:04:55,795 --> 00:04:58,498
the war made some rich,
ruined others,

60
00:04:58,498 --> 00:05:00,133
and changed forever

61
00:05:00,133 --> 00:05:03,386
the lives of all
who lived through it...

62
00:05:03,386 --> 00:05:06,089
a lackluster clerk
from galena, illinois,

63
00:05:06,089 --> 00:05:08,808
a failure in everything
except marriage and war,

64
00:05:08,808 --> 00:05:12,061
who, in 3 years, would
be head of the union army

65
00:05:12,061 --> 00:05:15,848
and in 7, president
of the united states;

66
00:05:15,848 --> 00:05:19,102
an eccentric student of
theology and military tactics,

67
00:05:19,102 --> 00:05:20,186
a hypochondriac

68
00:05:20,737 --> 00:05:22,905
who rode into battle
with one hand raised

69
00:05:22,905 --> 00:05:27,243
"to keep," he said,
"the blood balanced;"

70
00:05:27,777 --> 00:05:29,412
a college professor
from maine,

71
00:05:29,412 --> 00:05:31,581
who, on a little hill
in pennsylvania,

72
00:05:31,581 --> 00:05:34,283
ordered an unlikely
textbook maneuver

73
00:05:34,283 --> 00:05:35,368
that saved the union army

74
00:05:35,368 --> 00:05:38,621
and possibly
the union itself...

75
00:05:39,706 --> 00:05:41,341
two ordinary soldiers--

76
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:44,594
one from providence,
rhode island,

77
00:05:44,594 --> 00:05:46,713
the other from
columbia, tennessee,

78
00:05:46,713 --> 00:05:48,348
who each served 4 years

79
00:05:48,881 --> 00:05:51,050
and together seemed to
have been everywhere

80
00:05:51,050 --> 00:05:54,854
during the war and lived
to tell the tale...

81
00:05:56,472 --> 00:05:59,192
the courtly,
unknowable aristocrat,

82
00:05:59,192 --> 00:06:01,894
who disapproved
of secession and slavery,

83
00:06:01,894 --> 00:06:03,529
yet went on
to defend them both

84
00:06:03,529 --> 00:06:05,698
at the head of one
of the greatest armies

85
00:06:05,698 --> 00:06:07,867
of all time;

86
00:06:07,867 --> 00:06:11,120
the runaway boy who
"stole himself" from slavery,

87
00:06:11,120 --> 00:06:13,823
recruited two regiments
of black soldiers,

88
00:06:13,823 --> 00:06:15,992
and helped transform
the civil war

89
00:06:15,992 --> 00:06:19,796
into a struggle for
the freedom for all americans.

90
00:06:21,414 --> 00:06:24,667
and then there was
the rough man from illinois,

91
00:06:24,667 --> 00:06:26,836
who would rise to be
the greatest president

92
00:06:26,836 --> 00:06:29,005
the country has ever seen.

93
00:06:32,258 --> 00:06:34,977
between 1861 and 1865,

94
00:06:34,977 --> 00:06:36,596
americans made war
on each other

95
00:06:37,680 --> 00:06:40,400
and killed each other
in great numbers,

96
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:42,568
if only to become
the kind of country

97
00:06:42,568 --> 00:06:44,187
that could
no longer conceive

98
00:06:44,187 --> 00:06:46,355
how that was possible.

99
00:06:47,990 --> 00:06:49,609
what began
as a bitter dispute

100
00:06:49,609 --> 00:06:52,328
over union
and states' rights

101
00:06:52,328 --> 00:06:53,946
ended as a struggle

102
00:06:53,946 --> 00:06:56,666
over the meaning
of freedom in america.

103
00:06:57,750 --> 00:07:00,453
at gettysburg in 1863,

104
00:07:00,453 --> 00:07:04,257
abraham lincoln said
perhaps more than he knew.

105
00:07:04,257 --> 00:07:08,594
the war was about
"a new birth of freedom."

106
00:07:16,719 --> 00:07:21,057
man: 1938--
75th anniversary of
the battle of gettysburg.

107
00:07:21,057 --> 00:07:23,776
spoke to the remaining
few civil war veterans.

108
00:07:23,776 --> 00:07:28,114
veterans of the blue
and the gray...

109
00:07:29,198 --> 00:07:33,536
on behalf of the people
of the united states,

110
00:07:33,536 --> 00:07:36,789
i accept this monument

111
00:07:36,789 --> 00:07:40,576
in the spirit of
brotherhood and peace.

112
00:07:41,127 --> 00:07:43,830
year after year,
the nation remembered.

113
00:07:43,830 --> 00:07:44,914
in 1930, veterans
of the union army

114
00:07:45,465 --> 00:07:47,633
marched in
cincinnati, ohio,

115
00:07:48,167 --> 00:07:49,802
4 years later,
in new york city.

116
00:07:49,802 --> 00:07:53,055
they and the surviving
veterans of the confederacy

117
00:07:53,055 --> 00:07:55,224
were the last link

118
00:07:55,224 --> 00:07:57,927
with the terrible conflict
that tore america apart

119
00:07:57,927 --> 00:08:01,180
from 1861 to 1865.

120
00:08:01,180 --> 00:08:04,433
the last civil war veteran
would die in 1959,

121
00:08:04,433 --> 00:08:07,153
of long-ago battles,

122
00:08:07,153 --> 00:08:10,940
only history and legends.

123
00:08:23,419 --> 00:08:26,656
any understanding
of this nation

124
00:08:26,656 --> 00:08:28,274
has to be based,
and i mean really based,

125
00:08:28,274 --> 00:08:30,443
on an understanding
of the civil war.

126
00:08:30,443 --> 00:08:31,527
i believe that firmly.

127
00:08:31,527 --> 00:08:32,612
it defined us.

128
00:08:32,612 --> 00:08:35,865
the revolution
did what it did.

129
00:08:35,865 --> 00:08:37,500
our involvement
in european wars,

130
00:08:37,500 --> 00:08:38,584
beginning with
the first world war,

131
00:08:38,584 --> 00:08:40,203
did what it did,

132
00:08:40,203 --> 00:08:44,006
but the civil war
defined us as what we are,

133
00:08:44,006 --> 00:08:48,344
and it opened us
to being what we became,

134
00:08:48,344 --> 00:08:51,047
uh, good and bad things.

135
00:08:51,047 --> 00:08:53,216
and it--
it is very necessary

136
00:08:53,216 --> 00:08:56,469
if you're
going to understand
the american character

137
00:08:56,469 --> 00:08:58,104
in the 20th century

138
00:08:58,104 --> 00:09:00,273
to learn about this
enormous catastrophe

139
00:09:00,273 --> 00:09:02,975
of the mid-19th century.

140
00:09:02,975 --> 00:09:05,695
it was the--
the crossroads
of our being,

141
00:09:05,695 --> 00:09:08,397
and it was a hell
of a crossroads.

142
00:09:08,397 --> 00:09:12,168
for me, the picture
of the civil war

143
00:09:12,168 --> 00:09:15,972
as a historic
phenomenon...

144
00:09:17,056 --> 00:09:18,674
is not
on the battlefield.

145
00:09:18,674 --> 00:09:20,309
it's not about weapons.

146
00:09:20,309 --> 00:09:21,928
it's not about soldiers,

147
00:09:21,928 --> 00:09:23,563
except to the extent

148
00:09:23,563 --> 00:09:25,731
that weapons
and soldiers

149
00:09:25,731 --> 00:09:28,434
at that crucial moment

150
00:09:28,434 --> 00:09:30,603
joined a discussion
about something higher,

151
00:09:30,603 --> 00:09:33,856
about humanity,
about human dignity,

152
00:09:33,856 --> 00:09:36,025
about human freedom.

153
00:09:39,779 --> 00:09:43,583
"whence shall we expect
the approach of danger?

154
00:09:43,583 --> 00:09:47,336
"shall some transatlantic
giant step the earth

155
00:09:47,336 --> 00:09:50,590
"and crush us at a blow?

156
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:51,674
"never.

157
00:09:51,674 --> 00:09:55,361
"all the armies
of europe and asia

158
00:09:55,361 --> 00:09:57,496
"could not by force
take a drink

159
00:09:57,496 --> 00:09:59,081
"from the ohio river

160
00:09:59,081 --> 00:10:01,217
"or make a track
on the blue ridge

161
00:10:01,217 --> 00:10:04,420
"in the trial of
a thousand years.

162
00:10:04,420 --> 00:10:06,022
"if destruction
be our lot,

163
00:10:06,022 --> 00:10:10,893
"we must ourselves be
its author and finisher.

164
00:10:10,893 --> 00:10:16,315
"as a nation of free men,
we will live forever...

165
00:10:16,315 --> 00:10:18,484
or die by suicide."

